NWE heating oil premiums steady as freeze persists . Freezing weather gave strong support to NWE heating oil on Friday , but transport problems caused by iced - up canals and pipes curbed buying interest and prevented outright gains in differentials , traders said . Benchmark Jan and Feb IPE futures shed $ 4 . 25 and $ 3 . 50 to $ 227 . 75 and $ 222 . 75 a tonne respectively on bearish U . S . stock data . Heating oil refinery grade barges traded at Jan IPE + $ 2 . 50 for loading on Monday and at Jan IPE + $ 2 for loading on Tuesday , but material for mid - month went unchanged at + $ 1 . 25 / + $ 1 . 50 . Low sulphur diesel was steady at around Jan IPE + $ 11 / 12 . Cargoes saw scattered buying into France and Germany . A 20 , 000 tonne refinery grade heating oil cargo traded at Feb IPE + $ 8 . 25 for Jan 10 - 20 cif Hamburg , around unchanged . In cargoes , traders concentrated on trying to obtain heating oil and low sulphur diesel under arbitrage from the U . S . Gulf . Two 60 , 000 tonne heating oil vessels were booked from the U . S . Gulf but traders said both had options for a variety of destinations apart from Europe . The arb to Asia remains closed . A Wall Street trader was rumoured seeking to move Russian low sulphur diesel into Amsterdam . - - William Maclean , London newsroom + 44 171 542 7646 
